<subSubSection id="C32D63FDDE4DFFF3FF3FF653FB194958" pageId="19" pageNumber="35" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B883076DE4DFFF3FF3FF653FEDD487B" blockId="19.[189,335,1036,1062]" box="[189,335,1036,1062]" pageId="19" pageNumber="35">
<heading id="D0C0871ADE4DFFF3FF3FF653FEDD487B" bold="true" box="[189,335,1036,1062]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="19" pageNumber="35" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE4DFFF3FF3FF653FEDD487B" bold="true" box="[189,335,1036,1062]" pageId="19" pageNumber="35">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B883076DE4DFFF3FF3FF664FB194958" blockId="19.[187,1401,1083,1285]" pageId="19" pageNumber="35">
Colony spindle-shaped having six to nine zooids, more or less rectangular in each longitudinal row (
<figureCitation id="130C2CF3DE4DFFF3FF44F601FEA34825" box="[198,305,1118,1144]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="18.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[258,1330,643,1890]" captionTargetId="figure-104@18.[258,1330,643,1890]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Fig. 12. Skylonia sandbergi Sandberg, 1962 (GIS/B 0549). A. General view of the colony showing autozooids and well-developed knobs bordering the aperture. B. Close-up of the colony showing autozooids and well-developed knobs (arrows)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6580810" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6580810/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="35">Fig. 12A</figureCitation>
). Length and width of a few complete spindles vary between 
<quantity id="4CCF9D93DE4DFFF3FC72F601FBDB4825" box="[1008,1097,1118,1144]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="35" unit="mm" value="0.8">0.8 mm</quantity>
and 
<quantity id="4CCF9D93DE4DFFF3FBFCF601FB484825" box="[1150,1242,1118,1144]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="35" unit="mm" value="0.3">0.3 mm</quantity>
, respectively. Spindles have maximum diameter at or just below central point. Width/length ratio of median zooids varies between 
<quantity id="4CCF9D93DE4DFFF3FEF9F6FBFE4A48E2" box="[379,472,1188,1215]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="35" unit="mm" value="0.3">0.3 mm</quantity>
to 
<quantity id="4CCF9D93DE4DFFF3FD80F6FBFDF048E2" box="[514,610,1188,1215]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="35" unit="mm" value="0.8">0.8 mm</quantity>
. Width of apertures ranges from 
<quantity id="4CCF9D93DE4DFFF3FC76F6FBFBCD48E2" box="[1012,1119,1188,1215]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="35" unit="mm" value="0.05">0.05 mm</quantity>
to 
<quantity id="4CCF9D93DE4DFFF3FB08F6FBFB6A48E2" box="[1162,1272,1188,1215]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7" pageId="19" pageNumber="35" unit="mm" value="0.07">0.07 mm</quantity>
. Apertures above greatest diameter of spindles open obliquely upwards. End of frontal cover depressed, forming shallow groove. Usually very well-developed knobs bordering aperture (
<figureCitation id="130C2CF3DE4DFFF3FB91F6B4FBEC4958" box="[1043,1150,1259,1285]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="18.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[258,1330,643,1890]" captionTargetId="figure-104@18.[258,1330,643,1890]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Fig. 12. Skylonia sandbergi Sandberg, 1962 (GIS/B 0549). A. General view of the colony showing autozooids and well-developed knobs bordering the aperture. B. Close-up of the colony showing autozooids and well-developed knobs (arrows)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6580810" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6580810/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="35">Fig. 12B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32D63FDDE4DFFF3FF3FF773FC3D4A5C" pageId="19" pageNumber="35" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B883076DE4DFFF3FF3FF773FEA2491B" blockId="19.[189,304,1324,1350]" box="[189,304,1324,1350]" pageId="19" pageNumber="35">
<heading id="D0C0871ADE4DFFF3FF3FF773FEA2491B" bold="true" box="[189,304,1324,1350]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="19" pageNumber="35" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE4DFFF3FF3FF773FEA2491B" bold="true" box="[189,304,1324,1350]" pageId="19" pageNumber="35">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B883076DE4DFFF3FF3FF704FC3D4A5C" blockId="19.[187,1399,1370,1538]" pageId="19" pageNumber="35">
The present Kachchh species differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C374BF5DE4DFFF3FD1FF704FB8C4929" authority="Thomas, 1961" authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1961" box="[669,1054,1370,1397]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Skyloniidae" genus="Skylonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="19" pageNumber="35" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="mirabilis">
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE4DFFF3FD1FF704FCE14928" box="[669,883,1371,1397]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="35">Skylonia mirabilis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFA64D87DE4DFFF3FCFAF704FB8C4929" author="Thomas H. D." box="[888,1054,1370,1397]" pageId="19" pageNumber="35" pagination="359 - 363" refId="ref8684" refString="Thomas H. D. 1961. Skylonia mirabilis gen. et sp. nov., a problematical fossil from the Miocene of Kenya. Annals and Magazine of Natural History Series 13, 4: 359 - 363." type="journal article" year="1961">
Thomas, 
<quantity id="4CCF9D93DE4DFFF3FC61F705FB8C4929" box="[995,1054,1370,1396]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.98094" pageId="19" pageNumber="35" unit="in" value="1961.0">1961</quantity>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
in the shape of the autozooids and orifice (see Keij 1973: 224, pl. 3 figs 10–13). Compared to the present species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C374BF5DE4DFFF3FB0BF721FE9349E1" authority="(Sandberg, 1962)" baseAuthorityName="Sandberg" baseAuthorityYear="1962" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Skyloniidae" genus="Skylonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="19" pageNumber="35" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="dohmi">
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE4DFFF3FB0BF721FB6249C5" box="[1161,1264,1406,1432]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="35">S. dohmi</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFA64D87DE4DFFF3FB7DF721FF6B49E1" author="Sandberg P. A." pageId="19" pageNumber="35" pagination="61 - 66" refId="ref8182" refString="Sandberg P. A. 1962. New cheilostome Bryozoa from the Miocene of the Dominican Republic. Micropaleontology 8: 61 - 66." type="journal article" year="1962">Sandberg, 1962</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C374BF5DE4DFFF3FEBDF7FEFDD249E6" authority="Keij, 1973" authorityName="Keij" authorityYear="1973" box="[319,576,1441,1467]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Skyloniidae" genus="Skylonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="19" pageNumber="35" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="thomasi">
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE4DFFF3FEBDF7FEFE2E49E6" box="[319,444,1441,1467]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="35">S. thomasi</emphasis>
Keij, 1973
</taxonomicName>
have fewer autozooids in each longitudinal row, knobs adjoining the orifice, and a raised border around the orifice. 
<taxonomicName id="4C374BF5DE4DFFF3FD5FF79BFB484983" authority="Sonar &amp; Badve, 2019" authorityName="Sonar &amp; Badve" authorityYear="2019" box="[733,1242,1476,1502]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Skyloniidae" genus="Skylonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="19" pageNumber="35" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="malabarica">
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE4DFFF3FD5FF79BFC414983" box="[733,979,1476,1502]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="35">Skylonia malabarica</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFA64D87DE4DFFF3FC59F79BFB484983" author="Sonar M. A. &amp; Badve R. M." box="[987,1242,1476,1502]" pageId="19" pageNumber="35" pagination="583 - 593" refId="ref8495" refString="Sonar M. A. &amp; Badve R. M. 2019. Bryozoan fauna from the Burdigalian of Quilon Beds of Padappakara, Kerala, India. Journal of the Geological Society of India 93: 583 - 593. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 12594 - 019 - 1220 - y" type="journal article" year="2019">Sonar &amp; Badve, 2019</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
differs in the number of zooids and the nature of the knobs around the orifice.
</paragraph>
